title: A PHASE 1, DOUBLE-BLIND, PLACEBO-CONTROLLED, SPONSOR OPEN, RANDOMIZED, MULTIPLE DOSE STUDY TO EVALUATE THE SAFETY, TOLERABILITY, AND PHARMACOKINETICS OF PF-04447943 IN MILD TO MODERATE ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE SUBJECTS ON STABLE DONEPEZIL THERAPY
description_brief: The purpose of the study is to evaluate the safety of PF-04447943 when given in combination with donepezil in subjects who have Alzheimer's Disease. The study will also evaluate the absorption and distribution of both PF-04447943 and donepezil.

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails: Eligible participants enrolled in this study were already on prior stable donepezil therapy.

outcomeMeasures.title: Number of Participants With Vital Signs Abnormalities of Potential Clinical Concern
outcomeMeasures.description: Criteria for vital signs abnormalities of potential concern included: supine/standing systolic blood pressure (BP) (less than \[\<\] 90 millimeter of mercury \[mmHg\], maximum \[max\] decrease and increase of greater than or equal to \[\>=\] 30 mmHg from baseline); diastolic BP (\<50 mmHg, maximum decrease and increase of \>=20 mmHg from baseline); supine pulse rate \<40 beats per minute \[bpm\] or greater than \[\>\]120 bpm); standing pulse rate \<40 bpm or \>140 bpm. Baseline is defined as the last pre-dose (PF-04447943) recording at Day 0.

outcomeMeasures.title: Number of Participants With Electrocardiogram (ECG) Abnormalities of Potential Clinical Concern
outcomeMeasures.description: Criteria for ECG abnormalities of potential clinical concern included: PR interval (\>=300 milliseconds \[msec\], \>= 25 percent \[%\] increase when baseline \>200 msec or increase \>=50% when baseline less than or equal to \[\<=\] 200 msec); QRS interval (\>=200 msec, \>= 25% increase when baseline \>100 msec or increase \>=50% when baseline \<=100 msec); QT corrected using Fridericia's formula (QTcF) (\>=500 msec, maximum increase between \>=30 to \<60 msec and \>=60 msec). Baseline is defined as the last pre-dose (PF-04447943) recording at Day 0.

outcomeMeasures.title: Number of Participants With Laboratory Test Abnormalities
outcomeMeasures.description: Criteria for laboratory tests abnormalities included: hemoglobin, hematocrit (\<0.8\*lower limit of normal \[LLN\]); red blood cell count (\<0.8\*LLN); platelets (\<0.5\*LLN or \>1.75\* upper limit of normal \[ULN\]); leucocytes (\<0.6\*LLN or \>1.5\*ULN); lymphocytes, total neutrophils (\<0.8\*LLN or \>1.2\*ULN); basophils, eosinophils, monocytes (\>1.2\*ULN); total bilirubin (\>1.5\* ULN); aspartate aminotransferase, alanine aminotransferase, alkaline phosphatase (\>3\*ULN); creatinine, blood urea nitrogen (\>1.3\*ULN); glucose (\<0.6\*LLN or \>1.5\*ULN); uric acid (\>1.2\*ULN); sodium (\<0.95\*LLN or 1.05\*ULN); potassium, calcium, chloride, bicarbonate (\<0.9\*LLN or 1.1\*ULN); albumin, total protein (\<0.8\*LLN or 1.2\*ULN); urine analysis. Total number of participants with any laboratory abnormalities was reported.

outcomeMeasures.title: Number of Participants With Treatment-Emergent Adverse Events (AEs) and Serious Adverse Events (SAEs)
outcomeMeasures.description: An AE was any untoward medical occurrence in a participant who received study drug without regard to possibility of causal relationship. An SAE was an AE resulting in any of the following outcomes or deemed significant for any other reason: death; initial or prolonged inpatient hospitalization; life-threatening experience (immediate risk of dying); persistent or significant disability/incapacity; congenital anomaly. Treatment-emergent are events between first dose of study drug and up to Day 10 after last dose that were absent before treatment or that worsened relative to pretreatment state. Any abnormalities related to physical and neurological findings, laboratory tests, vital signs and ECG were reported as adverse events. AEs included SAEs as well as non-serious AEs which occurred during the trial.

certainAgreement.otherDetails: Pfizer has the right to review disclosures, requesting a delay of less than 60 days. Investigator will postpone single center publications until after disclosure of pooled data (all sites), less than 12 months from study completion/termination at all participating sites. Investigator may not disclose previously undisclosed confidential information other than study results.

drug: donepezil (background cholinesterase inhibitor used in the trial)
placebo: placebo (used as comparator in the randomized trial)
explanation_target: Reason: The investigational agent PF-04447943 is a selective phosphodiesterase-9A (PDE9A) inhibitor that elevates cGMP in brain/CSF, enhances synaptic plasticity and improved memory in preclinical models — i.e., a pharmacologic approach intended to enhance cognition rather than directly remove amyloid or tau pathology. citeturn0search0turn0search1

Act: The trial description and title state PF-04447943 was tested in mild–moderate AD subjects on stable donepezil to evaluate safety, tolerability and pharmacokinetics, with placebo control — consistent with a cognitive-enhancement add-on study rather than a disease-modifying biologic or pathology-targeting small molecule. (See clinical trial registry / study summaries). citeturn0search7turn0search3

Reflect: Given PF-04447943 is a small-molecule PDE9A inhibitor whose preclinical and clinical rationale is to boost cGMP/signaling and improve memory/attention, the correct category is 'cognitive enhancer'. There is no indication in the description that the drug is a biologic (antibody/vaccine) or directly targets core AD pathology (amyloid or tau) for disease modification. citeturn0search1turn0search5

Web search results used: - PF-04447943 described as a potent, selective PDE9A inhibitor that elevates cGMP and enhances synaptic plasticity / memory. citeturn0search0turn0search1 - Phase 1/Phase 2 study descriptions and safety/PK trials of PF-04447943 (including combinations with donepezil) corroborating the trial purpose and design. citeturn0search7turn0search3
explanation_agent: Reason: PF-04447943 is a selective phosphodiesterase‑9A (PDE9A) inhibitor that elevates cGMP in brain/CSF and was developed to enhance synaptic plasticity and improve memory (a cognitive‑enhancement mechanism), not to target amyloid or tau pathology. citeturn0search4turn0search0
